{ When the defending rook sits on the long side of the pawn (the side with more files between the rook and the pawn's file), the defender draws by placing the rook behind the pawn's queening rank, cutting the king off from the a7-square. Black's key move is Ra7+, forcing the rook onto the back rank (Ra8), after which perpetual checking along the a-file holds the draw. The long-side defense works here because White's king cannot step off the e-file without allowing the rook to reach a8 first. }
1... Ra7+ 2. Rd7 Ra8 { The simplest defensive methods: Black prevents the positions with the pawn on seventh Rank. } (2... Ra1 3. Ke8+ (3. Rd6 Ra8!) 3... Kf6 4. e7 Ke6 5. Kf8 Rf1+ 6. Ke8 Ra1 $10) 3. Rd8 (3. Kd6+ Kf6 4. Rf7+ Kg6) (3. Rb7 Kg6 4. Kd6 Kf6 5. e7 Kf7) (3. Rd6 { [%cal Ga8a7] } 3... Kg6) 3... Ra7+ 4. Kd6 Ra6+ 5. Ke5 Ra5+ 6. Rd5 Ra8 7. Rd7+ Kg6 { The reason of draw is the position is rook: it was placed on long side } *


