[UTCTime "07:13:02"]

{ The Lucena position is the most important theoretical position in rook and pawn versus rook endgames — the attacking side wins by "building a bridge." White's king is blocking its own pawn — it occupies b8, the promotion square, with the pawn on b7 directly behind it — and must step aside to let the pawn queen, but doing so exposes it to rear checks from Black's rook; the winning technique solves this in two steps: 1.Rd1+ drives the defending king away, then 2.Rd4! posts the rook on the fourth rank. Now when the white king steps off b8 and Black's rook starts checking, the Rd4 rook slides to Rb4 to interpose — shielding the king so the b-pawn promotes. The bridge rank adapts to whichever pawn file is involved; the principle is always the same. }
{ [%cal Bc1d1,Bd1d4,Bd4b4] }
1. Rd1+ Ke7 2. Rd4! { The bridge } 2... Ra1 3. Kc7 Rc1+ 4. Kb6 Rb1+ 5. Kc6 Rc1+ 6. Kb5 Rb1+ 7. Rb4 *


