{ The Umbrella — a technique coined by GM Mark Dvoretsky: "a pawn that shelters the attacking king from the rain of checks of the defending rook." In this completely winning position, Black has multiple winning continuations; the game continued 1...f4!, chosen by Tomáš Polák against Petr Velička (1995 Czech Team Championship) to illustrate the concept: after 2.gxf4, Black plays 2...Rb2+ to drive the White king away, then 3...Kf3 — the king shelters behind the f4-pawn (the umbrella), occupying a safe square free from rook harassment, while the e3-pawn advances to e1=Q. The Umbrella is not a rescue technique here but a clean, elegant winning method among several. }
1... f4! 2. gxf4 Rb2+ 3. Kf1 Kf3 $19 { Black use the pawn f4 like an Umbrella for protecs the black king from checks } 4. Ra1 Rh2 5. Kg1 Rg2+ 6. Kh1 Rg8 7. Kh2 e2 8. f5 Kf2 9. Kh3 Rg5! (9... e1=Q?? 10. Rxe1! Kxe1 11. Kh4! $10) *


