{ From Alexander Zaitsev vs Robert Hübner, Anderssen Memorial Büsum 1969 — a position illustrating the cardinal rule of rook endgames: an active rook draws, a passive rook loses. Multiple first moves draw (Rb4, Ra5, Rc5) because the drawing mechanism is always the same: when White plays f5, Black maneuvers the rook to the g-file (g1 or g2) to attack the g4 pawn from behind, and after White's king advances to g6, captures with Rxg4+ Kxf6 — reaching an equal ending. The only requirement is that the rook be active enough to reach the g-file in time when f5 comes. The losing blunder 1...Rb1?? fails precisely because the rook is too far from the action: it cannot reach the g-file in time, White marches the king to h5 and advances the pawns, and the rook cannot stop them from the back rank. }
1... Rb1?? (1... Rb4 2. f5 Rb1! 3. Kh5 Rg1!) (1... Ra5 2. g5 (2. f5 Ra1!) 2... fxg5+ 3. fxg5 Ra6 $10 (3... Ra8 $10)) 2. Kh5 Rg1 3. g5 fxg5 4. f5! Kf8 5. f6 $18 *



