{ From Alexander Kochiev vs Vasily Smyslov — 7th World Champion and co-author of Rook Endings — Soviet Zonal, Lvov 1978. This is a deeply theoretical draw with many critical branches, each requiring precise responses — consider watching the engines play and analyzing before practicing. The core principle: White must keep the rook active on the long side (Ra1, Rf1, or Rb1) to maintain checking distance and contest the pawn. The one clear mistake is 1.Ke2?? from the start — passive king retreat surrenders all defensive resources; Smyslov exploited it with Rd5!, supporting the pawn while escaping the checks, and converted without difficulty. }
1. Ke2?? { Both 1.Ke4 and 1. Rh1 might lead to draw } 1... Kb5 2. Rb1+ Ka4 3. Rc1 Kb4 4. Rb1+ Ka3! 5. Rc1 Rd5! 6. Ke3 Kb2 7. Rc4 Kb3 *


