[UTCTime "08:12:32"]

{ Chéron's study demonstrates a crucial exception to the Rule of Five: even when the formula says White wins (pawn rank 4 + king cut off 3 files = 7), the h-file edge provides Black a safe three-square shuffling corridor (h4-h5-h6) that White cannot break. The drawing precision is razor-thin: 1...Kh4! is the only drawing move — 1...Kh5 or 1...Kh6 lose immediately to 2.Rg7! cutting the king off from ranks 7-8. After 1.Rg2 Kh4 2.Rg7 Kh5 3.Rg1, Black must find 3...Kh6! — not 3...Kh4? which loses to 4.e5, nor 3...Ra8 which loses because the pawn outruns the rook. The key principle: when the defending king is trapped on the short side with the board edge as a wall, White has no room to outflank and the shuffle draws regardless of the Rule of Five. }
1. Rg2! (1. Kd4 Rd8+ 2. Kc5 Re8 3. Kd5 Rd8+ 4. Kc6 Re8 5. Re1 Kg6 6. Kd7 Ra8 (6... Re5 7. Kd6 Ra5)) 1... Kh4! 2. Rg7 (2. e5 Rxe5+ 3. Kf4 Kh3) 2... Kh5 3. Rg1! Kh6 (3... Kh4 4. e5) (3... Ra8 4. e5 Ra4 5. e6 Kh6 (5... Ra6 6. Kf4 Rxe6 7. Kf5) 6. e7 Ra8 7. Kf4 Re8 8. Kf5 Rxe7 9. Kf6) 4. Kd4 Rd8+ 5. Kc5 Re8 6. Kd5 Rd8+ 7. Ke6! Re8+ 8. Kf6! { It is important to remember that in case of a knight pawn, cuttinf off the king by two files is not sufficient to win } *


