{ Chéron's companion study to (I): here the defending king on e6 is close enough and active enough to draw, contrasting with (I) where it was stranded on g5. After 1.Rd4, Black's key defensive reply is 1...Ke5! — centralizing the king and attacking the rook; the pattern repeats: every time White plays Rd7, Black answers Ke6!, chasing the rook and denying White the free tempo to coordinate. If White tries marching the king (1.Ka4), Black draws with Ra8+ perpetual checks — the rook oscillates a8–b8 and the king cannot advance without walking into check. Passive rook moves (3...Rb8? or 3...Rc8+?) immediately lose because they abandon the king's active role — the draw rests entirely on the king harassing the attacking rook at every step. }
1. Rd4 (1. Ka4 Ra8+ 2. Kb5 Rb8+ 3. Ka5 Ra8+ 4. Kb6 Rb8+ 5. Kc5) 1... Ke5! 2. Kc3 (2. Rd7 Ke6! 3. Ra7 Kd6 4. Ka4 Kc6 $10) 2... Rh8 (2... Rc8+ 3. Rc4 (3. Kd3 Rb8) 3... Rb8 4. Rc6 Kd5 5. Ra6 Rc8+ 6. Kb3 Rc6!) 3. Rd7 (3. b5 Rb8 4. Rh4 Kd6 5. Kb4 Kc7 $10) 3... Ke6! (3... Rb8? 4. Kc4 Ke6 5. Ra7 Kd6 6. b5 Rc8+ 7. Kb4 Rc7 8. b6) (3... Rc8+? 4. Kb3 Ke6 5. Rd4 Ke5 6. Rc4 Rb8 7. Rc6 Kd5 8. Ra6) *


