{ A critical moment where White must choose the correct recapture after Black's pawn exchange. After 1...hxg3, recapturing 2.hxg3? allows Black to draw with 2...g4+! — stripping away the f3-pawn and reaching equality. The winning recapture is 2.Kxg3!, and crucially after 2...Kh7 White must play 3.h4! — pushing the h-pawn immediately to create a passed pawn and neutralize Black's g-pawn. This example shows that in rook endings with multiple pawns, the choice of recapture and pawn-break timing can be the difference between winning and drawing. }
1... hxg3 2. hxg3? (2. Kxg3! Kh7 3. h4! gxh4+ 4. Kh3 Kg7 5. f4! { [%cal Rf4f5,Rf5f6] }) 2... g4+! 3. fxg4 Rc1 $10 *


