[UTCTime "15:50:39"]

{ The Vancura position, named after Czech study composer Josef Vančura (1898–1921; study published posthumously 1924), is the main drawing technique for the defender against a rook pawn on the fifth or sixth rank — once the pawn reaches the seventh rank the defense generally breaks down. The key idea is to attack the pawn from the side with 1...Rf1+! followed by 2...Rf6!, placing the rook on the sixth rank where it simultaneously attacks the a6-pawn and delivers horizontal checks whenever the king tries to approach. The defending king stays near the kingside to avoid being cut off, and Black perpetually checks from behind whenever the white king advances to protect the pawn. Compare with the Romanovsky study (next chapter), which demonstrates the limits of this method. }
1... Rf1+! (1... Kf7? 2. Ke4 Ke7 (2... Ra5? 3. Kd4 Kg7 4. Kc4 Kf7 5. Kb4 Ra1 6. Kb5 Rb1+ 7. Kc6 Ra1 8. Kb7 Rb1+ 9. Ka7 Ke7 10. Rb8 Rc1 11. Kb7 Rb1+ 12. Ka8 Ra1 13. a7 Kd7 14. Kb7 Rb1+ 15. Ka6 Ra1+ 16. Kb6 Rb1+ 17. Kc5 Rc1+ 18. Kd4 Rd1+ 19. Kc3 Rc1+ 20. Kd2) 3. a7 Kf7 4. Rh8) 2. Ke4 Rf6! 3. Kd5 Rb6! 4. Kc5 Rf6! 5. Kb5 Rf5+ *


